<p>There are <strong>n</strong> lots on one side of a street (where <strong>n</strong> ≤ 500). We would like to erect at most <strong>k</strong> apartment buildings on these lots. Each building must occupy an interval of at most <strong>t</strong> consecutive lots. Moreover, each lot <strong>i</strong> has a height restriction <strong>r[i]</strong> (where <strong>r[i]</strong> ≤ 100). A building cannot exceed any of the height restriction of any lot on which it is built (that is, the maximal height of the building that can be erected on lot <strong>i</strong> to <strong>j</strong> is:</p>
<p><strong>H = min{r[i], r[i + 1], ..., r[j]})</strong></p>
<p>Hence, the maximum usable facade space of the building is: <strong>H × (j − i + 1)</strong>. We would like to have a program to select at most <strong>k</strong> non-overlapping intervals to erect the buildings such that the total usable facade space is maximized.</p>
<h3>Example 1</h3>
<p>Consider a street of length 10. The height restriction of each lot is as follows:</p>
<pre>7, 3, 12, 11, 13, 4, 8, 6, 6, 20</pre>
<p>Suppose we would like to erect at most <strong>k</strong> = 2 buildings and each building occu- pies at most <strong>t</strong> = 4 lots. Then, to maximize the total usable facade space, we choose two intervals <strong>r</strong>[3..5] = (12, 11, 13) and <strong>r</strong>[7..10] = (8, 6, 6, 20) (see “Example 1” in the figure below). The maximum usable facade space is 3 ∗ min{12, 11, 13} + 4 ∗ min{8, 6, 6, 20} = 57.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Example 2</h3>
<p>Suppose we would like to erect at most <strong>k</strong> = 3 buildings on the same street with the same height restrictions as in Example 1, and each building occupies at most <strong>t</strong> = 4 lots. Then, to maximize the total usable facade space, we choose three intervals <strong>r</strong>[3..5] = (12, 11, 13), <strong>r</strong>[7..9] = (8, 6, 6) and <strong>r</strong>[10..10] = (20) (see “Example 2” in the figure above). The maximum usable facade space is 3 ∗ min{12, 11, 13} + 3 ∗ min{8, 6, 6} + 1 ∗ 20 = 71.</p>
<h3>Input</h3>
<p>The input file is as follows: The first line contains three integers <strong>n</strong>, <strong>k</strong>, and <strong>t</strong> separated by a space character, where 1 ≤ <strong>n</strong> ≤ 500, 1 ≤ <strong>k</strong> ≤ n, and 1 ≤ <strong>t</strong> ≤ n. The rest of the <strong>n</strong>lines contain <strong>n</strong> positive integers representing the height restriction for the <strong>n</strong> lots. For Example 1, the input file looks like:</p>
<pre>10 2 4
7
3
12
11
13
4
8
6
6
20
</pre>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The input should be read from the standard input, and your program will be run several times, each one with one of the test cases.</p>
<h3>Output</h3>
<p>The output file contains an integer which is the maximum usable facade space. For the above example, the output file looks like:</p>
<pre>57
</pre>
